et form of   Agnes   and   Agatha ."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agatha de Clere was born about 1224, in Bramley, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, her father, Roger de Clere III, was 28 and her mother, Maud De Faye, was 32. She married William le Rus about 1243, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died before 27 December 1261, in Ludborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1224–Bef 27 December 1261":"umbes 1224–enne 27. detsembrit 1261","1224–1261":"1224–1261","1228–1291":"1228–1291","1229–1241":"1229–1241","1220–1253":"1220–1253","1245–1301":"1245–1301","1198–1247":"1198–1247","1193–Female":"1193–Surnud","25 December 1245":"25. detsember 1245","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1241":"1241","1261":"1261","abt 1243":"umbes 1243","1193":"1193","1291":"1291","1228":"1228","1247":"1247","1301":"1301","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1224":"umbes 1224","Bef 27 December 1261":"enne 27. detsembrit 1261","1229":"1229","Ludborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ludborough, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bramley, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Bramley, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fressingfield, S